## PART 5 — DOCUMENTATION AND ADR STRUCTURE

```
docs/
├── DESIGN.md                   # Hub: one-paragraph description + link to every doc
├── API-HTTP.md                 # Authoritative REST contract
├── API-SSE.md                  # Authoritative SSE contract
├── PERSISTENCE.md
├── RUNTIME-ENV.md              # Every T2A_* env var: name, type, default, required
├── OBSERVABILITY.md
├── EXECUTION-CYCLES.md
├── EXTENSIBILITY.md            # How to add a new resource end-to-end
└── adr/
    ├── ADR-0001-monorepo.md
    └── ADR-NNNN-<slug>.md      # One file per decision
```

### ADR Format

```markdown
# ADR-NNNN: <Short Title>

**Date:** YYYY-MM-DD
**Status:** Proposed | Accepted | Deprecated | Superseded by ADR-XXXX
**Deciders:** [names or roles]

## Context
What situation forced this decision? What constraints existed?

## Decision
What was decided? State it precisely.

## Consequences
### Positive
- ...
### Negative / Trade-offs
- ...

## Alternatives Considered
| Alternative | Reason Rejected |
|-------------|-----------------|
```

### Documentation Rules

- Every public HTTP route must appear in `docs/API-HTTP.md` before the handler is merged.
- Every `T2A_*` env variable used in code must appear in `docs/RUNTIME-ENV.md`.
- Any change that alters observable behavior (status codes, JSON fields, SSE event names) requires a doc update in the same commit.
- Write an ADR when: a structural decision affects more than one package, a technology is added or removed, or a team disagreed during review.

