## PART 6 — SPLITTING DECISION GUIDE

### Go Splitting Patterns

| Symptom | Correct Split |
|---------|---------------|
| Handler file has multiple resource groups | One file per resource: `handler_tasks.go`, `handler_cycles.go` |
| Handler file has many DTO types | Extract to `handler_tasks_json.go` |
| Store file has too many methods for one entity | `store_tasks_read.go` / `store_tasks_write.go` |
| Domain file has types AND state machine logic | `task.go` (types) + `transitions.go` (logic) |
| `main.go` has server config and startup | Extract `run()` to `internal/taskapi/server.go` |
| Middleware file has multiple unrelated concerns | One file per middleware |
| Test file > 600 lines | Extract fixtures to `testdata_test.go`, helpers to `helpers_test.go` |

### TypeScript/React Splitting Patterns

| Symptom | Correct Split |
|---------|---------------|
| Page component > 150 lines | Extract data fetching to container, rendering to children |
| Component imports from a sibling feature | The shared element belongs in `src/components/` or `src/types/` |
| Hook > 150 lines | Split query hooks from mutation hooks |
| API file has unrelated resources | One file per resource |
| Type file mixes wire types and UI state | `types/api.ts` (server contracts) vs feature-local types |
| Test file > 500 lines | Separate state tests from render tests; extract factories |

### When NOT to Split

Do not split solely to meet a line count target. A split is wrong if:

- The two resulting files would import each other (circular dependency — restructure instead).
- One of the resulting files would be < 30 lines.
- The split creates a new abstraction with no clear name.
- The split happens mid-function or mid-type-group.

